C&#x27;mon.<p>> Right away, you&#x27;ll notice a subtle difference – a more terse syntax is available to you when defining classes:<p><pre><code>    // The ES5 way
    var Photo = React.createClass({
      handleDoubleTap(e) { … },
      render() { … },
    });

    // The ES6+ way
    class Photo extends React.Component {
      handleDoubleTap(e) { … }
      render() { … }
    }
</code></pre>
It may or may not be more terse in longer examples, but ES6 already supports things to make the class syntax <i>less</i> terse here by about the same margin the article claims.
